title: For Sale:  Wilson Combat "Cave Gun" CQB with Rail, Tactical Light and EXTRAS!!
postcontent:
This Wilson Combat CQB with Tactical Rail is not your average CQB.  Look at the photo below of the serial number.  The letters “SF” in the serial number is Wilson Combat’s designation for Special Forces.  
If you are a serial number collector, or just like very nice 1911s, I have the pistol for you!
History of this gun:
I was approached by someone at my local range in December who shared the history of the limited run of Wilson "Cave Guns," which were developed for a custom order placed by our Special Forces units heading overseas. According to conversations they had with Wilson Combat, this select run with the SF prefix ended up never being delivered and went up for private sale.  I am NOT the original owner and I do NOT have the build sheet/test target.  I personally called Wilson Combat to see if they could mail me a copy of the build sheet to include with the sale of this pistol.  Wilson had a fire at their factory in 2006 and lost every piece of paper they had.  What Wilson COULD verify was that the gun was born in 2004 for the Special Forces.

This pistol has about 500 rounds down the chamber, and the finish is in fabulous condition. Please see the pictures and you'll be able to easily see the great shape the gun is in.


Included:
Streamlight TLR-1 Flashlight 
3 Wilson Combat Magazines 
Wilson Combat Bag
3 holsters I have for it.

The pistol comes with THREE 8-round Wilson magazines. Two of the Mags are new and have the bumper designed for a smaller grip size, and if you get a new bumper on there, it will work perfectly. 

The most exciting extra is a Raven Concealment custom molded holster designed for this pistol, as well as a Streamlight TLR-1 flashlight with option for an extended, threaded barrel.  These holsters take 6-8 months to receive on custom order, so this is a real steal.
There are two additional holsters I'm throwing in with this. One is an IWB, as well as a Blackhawk holster with paddle attachment.

Why am I selling? I'm trying to downsize my collection to fewer pistols. Otherwise, I love the way this baby shoots!

I really cannot answer any other questions about this pistol, as I don’t have the spec sheet from Wilson.



I reserve the right to end the auction at any time.
All items sold as is no exchanges or returns.
When you select your FFL Dealer they may fax or preferably email their FFL Documents to My FFL.
Please allow 1-3 business days for items to ship once payment and FFL are received.
Shipping is at the Buyer cost.  Handguns are shipped USPS priority mail.  Shipping IS INSURED by me.  Once payment and FFL are received we will email you a tracking/delivery confirmation number.

title: For Sale/Trade:  REMINGTON 721 RIFLE .30-06
postcontent:
"F.E.P." is actually "R.E.P." for Remington English Proof. Remington adopted that term simply to add a little cache to their product; their proof practices use SAAMI specs the same as everyone else. 

The history of those rifles is interesting. From 1921 up to WWII, Remington made sporting rifles (the Model 30 and variations) using Model 1917 receivers and parts left over from WWI production. They made only such parts as they had to. At the end of WWII, they decided that the M1917 ploy had about run its course. Even though they used some tricks to disguise the origin of the rifles, customers were aware that they were buying what was essentially a warmed over military rifle.

So they turned their engineers and designers, including the famous Mike Walker, loose with blank sheets of paper. The result was not one, but two rifles, the standard length 721 and the short action 722. The 722 was released with a brand new cartridge, the famous "triple deuce", the .222 Remington, from which came a whole slew of cartridges, including the military 5.56mm, aka the .223 Remington.

The 721/722 rifles were made to be affordable, a contrast to the Winchester 70, famed as the "Rifleman's Rifle" but quite expensive. The result of the desire to keep the price down was that the rifles were plain. While special treatment, even engraving and inlay, was available, the standard rifles had no checkering, trigger guards were stamped steel, and so on.

But they shot and shot well. A lot of owners wanted to upgrade, and for a while gun shops had bins full of take off stocks, replaced by better grade custom stocks. Eventually, Remington got the word and, using the same basic action, produced the Model 700, now I believe the best selling CF sporting rifle in the world.

There is a sad sidelight to the Remington success story. Winchester (Olin) was unable to admit that it was losing sales to Remington and began to focus on military surplus rifles as the source of their economic woes. So they persuaded Senator Tom Dodd, of CT, father of the current CT senator Chris Dodd, to include a ban on military surplus imports in his Gun Control Act of 1968, not hard to do after JFK was killed with a surplus rifle. In a nasty example of special interest lobbying, Winchester's attorneys even wrote that part of the law. There were hints that Dodd received more than thanks and campaign support, but nothing was ever proven.

title: For Sale:  Washington: Freedom Prevails in Olympia - Anti-Gun Legislation Dead for 2013
postcontent:
Freedom has prevailed again in Olympia!  Yesterday was the deadline for legislation to be voted out of its chamber of origin.  Thanks to your hard work and relentless opposition, House Bill 1588 failed to come up for a vote on the House floor.  The fate of the so-called “universal background check” legislation and your rights came down to the wire.                               

On Tuesday, the state House of Representatives came to a halt for more than seven hours as House Democrats tried to round up enough votes to pass this anti-gun measure.  As NRA-ILA previously reported, HB 1588 could have criminalized all private sales of firearms.

HB 1588, introduced by state Representative Jamie Pederson (D-43), was nothing more than a regulatory scheme that would have created a huge burden for law-abiding citizens, been unenforceable, and ignored by criminals.  This bill was nothing more than a precursor to Universal Firearm REGISTRATION. 

Your participation in the legislative process was essential to this victory! Although your Second Amendment rights were defended in Olympia during this round, the attack on your inherent right to self-defense and right to keep and bear arms is far from over.  Gun owners and sportsmen must remain vigilant in order to preserve our freedoms!

The following anti-gun bills are also dead for this session:

House Bill 1676, introduced by state Representative Ruth Kagi (D-32), a so-called “child access prevention” bill which would have singled out the storage of firearms for criminalization under certain circumstances. 

House Bill 1703, introduced by state Representative Laurie Jinkins (D-27), would have levied an outrageous tax on all firearm and ammunition purchases to create more bureaucracy in the form of a “firearm safety” education program.

Senate Bill 5737, introduced by state Senators Ed Murray (D-43) and Jeanne Kohl-Welles (D-36), would have banned commonly owned firearms mischaracterized as “assault weapons” and magazines that hold more than ten rounds.  This extreme measure would have also allowed in-home inspections by law enforcement.

Your NRA-ILA will continue to keep you informed as this legislative session continues and draws to its adjournment.  Caution: legislative rules can always be waived, so until the legislature adjourns on April 28, we must remain vigilant.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Anyone? Pre-WWII Mossberg&Sons Model 44b history?
postcontent:
I have recently received a Mossberg&Sons Model 44b in mint condition that does not have a Serial Number stamp, only the "Mossberg&Sons m44b" on the forward top portion of the barrel "no US stamp" and a hand stamped "Q" on the underside of the barrel just forward of the receiver. 
The rifle also sports what I can guess is the original Mossberg&Sons 4 aperture peep sight "that does not interfere with the removal of the bolt". Has a Lyman non-US stamped leather & brass sling just like the "US Property stamped" slings found on the M1 in WWII. I have a boat load of parts for this rifle as well including just about every type of sight "that I can tell" made for this gun both peeps & posts. the other interesting part is that there are signs of hand tooling between the trigger and bolt guide post and compared to several other M44b's I have handled the action is flawless and requires almost no effort to work.

Is there anyone out there who is still alive who may know about these early guns? I would most certainly appriciate any help in determining the origin and year of manufacture of this beautiful rifle! I can also provide high quality photos of any part of the rifle that may help in this search.
I thank you for your time taken to read and furthermore anyone who can help me track this history!
P Mercer
REDACTED
REDACTED

The history that I know of is that this rifle was used pre-WWII in Boy Scout Competition shooting teams as well as during and after WWII in the US Army Competition shooting teams. The man who owned the gun was a brilliant patent designer holding many patents for tools and equipment during and after WWII.
